    "abstractNote": "While the vast majority of manuscripts portray Jesus in Mark 1.41 as \u2018moved to compassion\u2019 (\u03c3\u03c0\u03bb\u03b1\u03b3\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03b8\u03b5\u03af\u03c2) before healing a leper, five putative witnesses in three languages depict him \u2018becoming angry\u2019 (\u1f40\u03c1\u03b3\u03b9\u03c3\u03b8\u03b5\u03af\u03c2/iratus). Following Hort's dictum that \u2018knowledge of documents should precede final judgments on readings\u2019, this article offers the first thorough examination of the witnesses to \u2018anger\u2019, with the result that the sole putative Syriac witness is dismissed, the Old Latin witnesses are geographically isolated, and the sole Greek witness linked to the Old Latin as a Greek\u2013Latin diglot. Since the final grounds for Jesus\u2019 \u2018anger\u2019, that it is the lectio difficilior, also prove insubstantial, \u03c3\u03c0\u03bb\u03b1\u03b3\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03b8\u03b5\u03af\u03c2 is concluded to be original, with \u2018anger\u2019 originating in the Old Latin manuscript tradition.",
